{{Orphan|date=October 2015}}
'''Cyber sovereignty''' is a phrase used in the field of internet governance to describe governments' desire to exercise control over the Internet within their own borders, including political, economic, cultural and technological activities. In his 2015 book ''[[Data and Goliath]]'', American security expert [[Bruce Schneier]] says the cyber sovereignty movement, in countries such as [[Russia]], [[China]], [[France]] and [[Saudi Arabia]], was given an enormous boost by the [[Global surveillance disclosures (2013–present)|2013 revelations of widespread international NSA surveillance]], which those countries pointed to as justification for their activities and evidence of U.S. hypocrisy on Internet freedom issues.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Data and Goliath: The Hidden Battles to Collect Your Data and Control Your World|last = Schneier|first = Bruce|publisher = W.W. Norton & Company|year = 2015|isbn = 978-0393244816|location = New York|pages = }}</ref>
== References == {{Reflist}}
