'''Marvin Lewis Kline''' (August 9, 1903 &ndash; April 9, 1974) was an architectural engineer and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politician who served as the 34th [[List of mayors of Minneapolis|mayor of Minneapolis]].
==Early life and career== Kline was born in [[Brunswick, Nebraska]] in 1903. His family moved to [[Redwood Falls, Minnesota]] in 1915 and Kline went on to attend the [[University of Minnesota]], graduating in 1929 with a degree in architectural engineering. He worked with the Minnesota Department of Transportation and later formed his own company. In 1935, he was elected to the Minneapolis City Council. He was re-elected to a second term in 1939 and became the council's president.<ref name=obit>{{cite news|title=M. L. Kline, Ex-Sister Kenny head, dies at 70|work=Minneapolis Tribune|date=14 April 1974}}</ref> ==Mayoralty== In 1941, Kline was elected mayor. During his time in office he worked with the city of [[St. Paul, Minnesota]] and the state government to form the jointly run [[Metropolitan Airports Commission]]. Kline was criticized by some (including journalist [[Arthur Kasherman]]) of [[corruption]] and [[Racketeering|collusion with the city's criminal underworld]]. According to a contemporaneous [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] document, the [[Special Agent in Charge|SAC]] Rhodes of the FBI field office in [[St. Paul]]{{#tag:ref|From 1941–1949, what is now the [[List of FBI field offices#Minneapolis|FBI Field Office in Minneapolis]] was located in [[St. Paul]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fbi.gov/history/field-office-histories/minneapolis |title=FBI Minneapolis History |date=August 13, 2016 |website=Federal Bureau of Investigation |language=en-us |format=HTML |publication-date=May 26, 2016 |access-date=2018-09-24 |laysource=FBI |laydate=2016}}</ref>|group="note"|name="FBI field office history"}} was also reported to believe that "Kline is controlled by the racketeers".<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://vault.fbi.gov/hubert%20h.-humphrey/hubert-h.-humphrey-part-01-of-32/view#document/p4 |title=Hubert H. Humphrey Part 01 of 32 |date=January 19, 1945 |last=Nichols |first=L. B. |type=Government memorandum |language=en-US |publisher=The Vault ([[FBI]] [[Freedom of Information Act|FOIA]] Library) |page=4 |format=PDF}}{{DoJ}}</ref> He was defeated in 1945 by [[Hubert Humphrey]] who ran on a platform of [[Law and order (politics)|law and order]] and cleaning up the city's government.<ref name=obit/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Solberg|first1=Carl|title=Hubert Humphrey: A Biography|date=2003|publisher=Minnesota Historical Society Press|isbn=9780873514736}}</ref><ref name=electiontrends>{{cite web|title=Career of Marvin Lewis Kline|url=http://electiontrendsproject.org/search/search.php?candidate=2|website=Minnesota Election Trends Project}}</ref> ==Later life and death== After leaving office, Kline worked with the [[Sister Kenny Rehabilitation Institute]] as their executive director. In 1964, Kline was convicted of [[grand larceny]] for illegally boosting his salary as director and for diverting fundraising proceeds from the institute's foundation. He was sentenced to [[Minnesota Correctional Facility – Stillwater|Stillwater Prison]] for 10 years but released after serving 3 years.<ref name=obit/>
After being released, Kline briefly worked as an engineer at the [[Twin Cities Army Ammunition Plant]] before suffering from a stroke and retiring. Kline died of a heart attack in [[Ventura, California]] in 1974. He is buried in [[Blair, Nebraska]].<ref name=obit/><ref>{{cite web|title=Marvin L. Kline (1903–1974)|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/66844981|website=Find A Grave}}</ref>
